The '''Manabe clan''' (間部氏, ''Manabe-shi'') was a [[Samurai]] and later [[Kazoku]] clan of [[Japan]]. Its rise to prominence began in the mid-[[Edo period]] with the elevation of [[Manabe Akifusa]] to [[daimyō]] status. Following the [[Meiji Restoration]], the family became part of the [[Kazoku]] peerage system as ''shishaku'' (''viscount''). The clan's hereditary title included the character 詮 (''sen'').

== History ==
Originally, the clan bore the name "Shiokawa" {{Sfn|Kansei Genealogies|1923|p=708}}. Under Okabe Akimitsu, they adopted "Manabe" after his mother's family, later altering the name to "Manabe" {{Sfn|Kansei Genealogies|1923|p=708}}. During the generation of Kiyosada, a descendant of Akimitsu, the family temporarily adopted the surnames Hoshino and Nishida before reverting to Manabe {{Sfn|Kansei Genealogies|1923|p=708}}.

Manabe Akimitsu's father, Manabe Sadaaki, is believed to have been part of a branch of the Manabe family, which ruled the local stronghold in [[Izumi Province]], at Tannowa.

Kiyosada's eldest son, Akifusa, served under Tokugawa Tsunayoshi (later [[Tokugawa Ienobu|Ienobu]]), during which time the surname officially changed to Manabe. As Ienobu became shōgun, Akifusa rose as a powerful aide, but his influence declined following the death of the 7th shōgun, [[Tokugawa Ietsugu]]. With the ascension of [[Tokugawa Yoshimune]], Akifusa was reassigned to the [[Murakami Domain]] in [[Echigo Province]]. His successor, [[Manabe Akitoki]], was later transferred to the [[Sabae Domain]] in Echizen Province, marking the clan's final territorial base.

Key figures in the clan's history include Akifusa, a prominent shogunal advisor, and [[Manabe Akikatsu]], who served as a senior [[Rōjū|Elder of the Bakufu]].

The last daimyō, [[Manabe Akimichi]], oversaw the clan's transition during the [[Meiji period]]. After the [[Abolition of the han system|abolition of the domains]] in 1871, the Manabe family was incorporated into the Kazoku system. In 1884, under the [[Kazoku|Kazoku peerage system]], the family received the Rank of ''shishaku'' (viscount) {{Sfn|Kodate|2006|p=336}}.

Under [[Manabe Akinobu]], the family resided in [[Hamadera]], [[Osaka Prefecture]] {{Sfn|Peerage Register|1990|p=194}}.

== Lineage of Heads ==
# [[Manabe Akifusa]] (''従四位下''). Lord of [[Echizen Province|Echizen]].
# [[Manabe Akitoki]] (''従五位下''). Lord of [[Shimōsa Province|Shimōsa]].
# [[Manabe Akimichi]] (''従五位下''). Lord of [[Tango Province|Tango]].
# [[Manabe Akinaka]] (''従五位下''). Lord of [[Shūzen]].
# [[Manabe Akishige]] (''従五位下''). Lord of Shimōsa.
# [[Manabe Akihiro]] (''従五位下''). Lord of [[Wakasa Province|Wakasa]].
# [[Manabe Akinobu]] (''従五位下''). Lord of Shūzen.
# [[Manabe Akikatsu]] (''従四位下''). Lord of Shimōsa.
# [[Manabe Akitomo]] (''従五位下''). Lord of [[Awa Province|Awa]].
# [[Manabe Akimichi]] (''正五位''). Last Daimyō; first viscount.
# [[Manabe Akinobu]] (''正三位''). Viscount {{Sfn|Peerage Register|1990|p=194}}.

