Kiyosada's eldest son, Akifusa, served under Tokugawa Tsunayoshi (later {{ill|Tokugawa Ienobu|en|Tokugawa Ienobu|qid=Q366734|lt=Ienobu|1=Tokugawa Ienobu}}), during which time the surname officially changed to Manabe. As Ienobu became shōgun, Akifusa rose as a powerful aide, but his influence declined following the death of the 7th shōgun, {{ill|Tokugawa Ietsugu|en|Tokugawa Ietsugu|qid=Q366722|lt=Tokugawa Ietsugu|1=Tokugawa Ietsugu}}. With the ascension of {{ill|Tokugawa Yoshimune|en|Tokugawa Yoshimune|qid=Q319664|lt=Tokugawa Yoshimune|1=Tokugawa Yoshimune}}, Akifusa was reassigned to the {{ill|Murakami Domain|en|Murakami Domain|qid=Q849483|lt=Murakami Domain|1=Murakami Domain}} in {{ill|Echigo Province|en|Echigo Province|qid=Q666514|lt=Echigo Province|1=Echigo Province}}. His successor, [[:en:Manabe Akitoki|Manabe Akitoki]], was later transferred to the {{ill|Sabae Domain|en|Sabae Domain|qid=Q3034517|lt=Sabae Domain|1=Sabae Domain}} in Echizen Province, marking the clan's final territorial base.

Key figures in the clan's history include Akifusa, a prominent shogunal advisor, and {{ill|Manabe Akikatsu|en|Manabe Akikatsu|qid=Q3285148|lt=Manabe Akikatsu|1=Manabe Akikatsu}}, who served as a senior [[Rōjū|Elder of the Bakufu]].

The last daimyō, [[:en:Manabe Akimichi|Manabe Akimichi]], oversaw the clan's transition during the {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|qid=Q3125096|lt=Meiji era|1=Meiji era}}. After the {{ill|Abolition of the han system|en|Abolition of the han system|qid=Q331905|lt=abolition of the domains|1=Abolition of the han system}} in 1871, the Manabe family was incorporated into the Kazoku system. In 1884, under the [[Kazoku|Kazoku peerage system]], the family received the Rank of ''shishaku'' (viscount) {{Sfn|Kodate|2006|p=336}}.

Under [[Manabe Akinobu]], the family resided in {{ill|Hamadera|en|Hamadera|qid=Q13637275|lt=Hamadera|1=Hamadera}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|en|Osaka Prefecture|qid=Q122723|lt=Osaka Prefecture|1=Osaka Prefecture}} {{Sfn|Peerage Register|1990|p=194}}.

